    # [Scene: Old Docks Community Hub | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Urgent strings under a steady percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain pattering; distant gulls]
    "You return to the Hub with a weight in your chest that makes your shoulders feel like ballast. The Atrium still rings in your head — polite questions, the Council’s clinical lights, Ari Nakamura’s unreadable look."
    "You chose the neighborhood; you doubled down. That choice is not a warm certainty so much as a thin rope stretched taut across a widening tide."
    "Nora meets you at the door with a toolbox and the kind of grin that is more warning than welcome. Samir follows, slow but steady, his cap pulled lower against the damp."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "We lost three donors off the crowdsourcing page overnight. Someone put up a competing fundraiser for 'immediate protection.' It's getting clicks."
    "You set your notebook on the nearest crate and flip to a page filled with hand-drawn transects, marsh plants, and a messy column of supply costs. Your pen feels too small for the scale of things."
    "You breathe in salt and sawdust and the faint sweetness of wet plants drying on racks."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "Then we make the human argument louder. Tell people what living shorelines do for fishermen, for kids, for elders. Show them Samir's maps, Nora's repair logs. Make it impossible to think of this as abstract."
    show samir_qureshi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "They'll listen if we show them it works. But it'll take time. And time is the thing we don't have."
    "Your jaw tightens. Time is a tide that does not negotiate."

    nora_daz "Reaching out to the gardeners' co-op tonight. Luca Chen's been fliering nonstop. We have the planting schedule but we need hands. And—' (she hesitates) '—money for biodegradable stakes. Council wants contingency plans. Elena asked that personally."
    "You feel that name in your ribs — Councilwoman Reyes, aluminum and restraint and election cycles. Her request sounds like cooperation but it tastes like pressure. You scribble 'contingency' at the top of the page, underlining it until the ink smears."

    maya_ortega "We give her contingency that centers residents. No relocations. No sidelining of local stewardship. Offer a staged plan — pilot plots, measurable metrics, a city-administered watch fund. We win both hearts and oversight."

    nora_daz "You think that'll be enough to keep a developer from buying the idea and turning it into a render?"

    samir_qureshi "Maya—' He uses your given name when the tide is higher than a laugh. 'We need to be honest with people who are hesitant. Not everyone will be convinced by maps."

    "The Hub fills with the low hum of people turning pages and tying knots. On a white board someone has written tonight’s schedule" "6pm — Marsh survey. 8pm — Planting prep. Midnight — Seed bank drop."

    maya_ortega "Your guilt tightens into a kind of focus — everything you do becomes proof against the pilot failure that haunts you. One misstep and the whole fragile trust could splinter."

    menu:
        "Lead the door-to-door persuasion team tonight":
            "You pull on your jacket and grab a stack of neighbors' stories. The Hub loosens with a ripple of relief as you move; people feel steadier when you step forward."
        "Organize supplies and coordinate remotely from the Hub":
            "You stay, routing volunteers and tallying donations. Your lists multiply; control is a dull, necessary ache. Lucia and Nora leave with quick, appreciative looks."

    # --- merge ---
    "The evening's work continues, converging back on the marsh preparations and the rising tide."
    # [Scene: Salt Marsh Reserve | Dusk]
    hide nora_daz
    hide maya_ortega
    hide samir_qureshi

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rapid percussive rhythms over a low, throbbing synth]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tide whispering, boots squelching, distant thunder]
    "The marsh is narrower than you remember and wider than you fear. You and Luca Chen step off the flattened boardwalk because the sturdy trail has been swallowed by last winter's tides. The air tastes fouled-sweet;"
    "a metal tang rides the salt. Each step sinks into a cold, reluctant give — the mud remembers every boot it has ever known."
    "Luca Chen moves like someone who grew up telling stories to tide charts. He speaks with his hands, sweeping arcs that shape plans into work. Up close, the salt lines his sleeves like a constellation."
    show luca_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_chen "We stagger plantings to let roots take. We weave cane with old fishing line to trap silt. It's not glamorous, but it holds. You know this."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "I know. I just—' The word cracks off. 'I keep seeing the pilot that failed first. We fixed it too late. People lost hope. I won't let that happen again."
    "Luca Chen stops, turning to you. His gaze is the shallow of the sea — honest, reflecting."

    luca_chen "Then let's do it loud. Let's make the marsh be seen. Bring Samir in as storyteller—people respect him. We'll have music, food, work shifts. Make it sticky in people's lives."
    "Hands muddy, you tie cord around a sapling and press it into the mud. The plant resists and then yields, an act of violence that is also a promise. The wind presses the sound of Lakota chanting from a radio on a distant dock; someone else’s ritual meets your own."

    maya_ortega "The closeness with Luca Chen is not sudden; it's in the easy hand-offs—he passes you the trowel, you share the blanket when the wind bites. Each small ritual stitches you to him and to the marsh."

    luca_chen "You always bring that old field notebook. You're going to outlive us all with your notes."
    "You flick mud from the corner of the cover. 'Someone has to,' you say. 'If the story isn't written, it doesn't count.'"

    "He smiles, small and full. The smile bows into seriousness" "If you ever leave this work to be someone else's story, I'll—"
    "Your heart speeds in a way that feels wrong and right at the same time. Outside, the clouds have gone signal-black, and the sea's voice is rising."

    menu:
        "Tell Luca Chen to stay near the boardwalk tonight":
            "You touch his arm. He nods, disappointed but understanding. He stays, pacing the line like a guardian, watching the sky."
        "Insist he comes into the flats with you":
            "He laughs, then takes your hand. You move together carefully. Every step is a small coalition against the tide."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices reconverge as the tide rises and the team scrambles to secure plants and volunteers."
    # [Scene: Old Docks | Night]
    hide luca_chen
    hide maya_ortega

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High, staccato strings; heartbeat synth]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Radio broadcast, the clack of keyboard keys, waves hitting pilings faster than before]

    "Back at the Docks the screens in a café glow with a headline" "Ari Nakamura's Seawall: A Model for the World."
    show nora_daz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "They're selling speed. Cameras love clean edges. Our work is messy and hates a camera lens."
    "You feel a fist of fury and helplessness. The city's appetite for something quick gnaws at the edges of everyone's resolve. Donations trickle in; the crowdsourcing thermometer crawls. Samir sits beside an open-case guitar, his fingers idly testing a string."
    show samir_qureshi at right:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "Elena called again. She wants hard contingencies by tomorrow. She said, 'I need to know you'll stop the bleeding if a storm comes.'"
    "You think of bleeding — roofs, livelihoods, a history peeled back. Elena's voice on the phone had been direct but not cold; it was the voice of someone balancing ballots and water levels and press conferences."
    "You owe the neighborhood plans that are accountable, but you also owe them safety without displacement."
    show maya_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "Draft the contingency. Short-term emergency steps, community watch rosters, an escrow for emergency repairs. We'll ask for city matching funds if the thermometer hits sixty percent."

    nora_daz "That's optimistic."

    maya_ortega "Then be optimistic enough for both of us."
    "You move through the crowd to check the line of newly planted stakes. A small team — volunteers, one elderly poet from the neighborhood, a group of teenagers on bikes — are tightening ropes along a fragile silt-trap. The sky is a bruise; the clouds are knives."

    "A text from Councilwoman Reyes pulses on your wrist. You step aside and read" "We need procedural assurances. Present contingency at 9am. We must show the Council we can handle escalation. For the record, your approach is being watched."
    "Your palms sweat. The word 'watched' is both protection and pressure."
    "Luca Chen arrives with two thermoses and a face lined in worry and determination. He squeezes your shoulder; you feel it as both comfort and a charge to move faster."
    hide nora_daz
    show luca_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    luca_chen "There's a shipment of stakes due at midnight, but the truckers are worried about the swell. They might cancel."
    "You taste metal in your mouth. Midnight is a thin line away."
    hide samir_qureshi
    show nora_daz at right:
        zoom 0.7

    nora_daz "If that truck doesn't show, we go smaller. We repurpose old boards, nets. We can't let the planting go unguarded."

    maya_ortega "Then we guard it ourselves."
    hide maya_ortega
    show samir_qureshi at center:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_qureshi "Maya—' He looks at you like a harbor looks at a storm — patient, pleading. 'You can't save everything alone."
    "Your reply is a cold certainty:"
    hide luca_chen
    show maya_ortega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "I don't want to be alone doing it."
    "The radios on the docks begin to pick up a weather alert. The calm has left the air. People move with a nervous choreography — folding tarps, fastening ladders, securing tools. Your breath comes quick and shallow."

    maya_ortega "Shelter the plants. Protect the volunteers. Keep Samir's stories from being drowned by headline noise. These priorities jostle like poorly lashed cargo. You have to decide which will keep the neighborhood intact and which will be the sacrifice."
    "Somewhere, a stake gives — a small, insignificant failure — but in the hub of adrenaline it feels enormous. Volunteers shout. A rope snaps. The ocean tests its patience on the flats."
    "You run. You don't think; you act. Your boots slip in tide-slick mud. Luca Chen is at your side; Nora is already ahead with a coil of rope. Samir calls out instructions that are more than helpful — they sound like prayers."
    "Hands reach, anchor, pull. A sapling rigs sideways and threatens to rip free; you lunge and grab its fragile stem. The world narrows to the strain in your fingers, the slick of mud under your nails, the roar of the swell approaching like a living thing with teeth."

    "Rain slants into your face and stings. A broken rope whips the air. The radio the volunteer carried blares a siren-tone warning" "High tide surge expected within twenty minutes."
    "Everything in you fixes into a single, brutal clarity. The future is not an essay anymore; it's a series of choices pressed into action in the next few breaths."
    "You look at Luca Chen. His jaw is set; his eyes are wide. He meets yours and says nothing — because there are no words that make the next seconds any less urgent."
    "Your chest rams with the knowledge that this night will decide more than a planting schedule. It will decide whether trust can meet test, whether the neighborhood's fragile gains are real."
    "You stand with mud to your knees and a sapling slipping from your grip. The tide is coming."
